<DOC><DOCNO> DOE2-25-0996 </DOCNO><TEXT>New gamma ray observations of Cygnus X-1, especially those with the HEAO-3satellite, have revealed a transient bump in the 0.4 - few move region.Its successful interpretation in terms of the optically thin emissionfrom a compact cloud of semi-relativistic plasma close to the black horizonhas shed new light on the structure and dynamics of the accretion flow.Detailed spectral and temporal analyses of the HEAO and other gamma raydata may thus provide an important new diagnostic of black holes notobtainable with x-ray observations. This has important implications forboth the theory and strategies of future high energy observation of blackholes. 33 refs., 8 figs., 1 tabs.</TEXT></DOC>